# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ambiguity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer was educated at Eton College and the University of Oxford, after which he studied the philosophy of logical positivism at the University of Vienna.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] From 1933 to 1940 he lectured on philosophy at Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] During the Second World War Ayer was a Special Operations Executive and MI6 agent.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer was Grote Professor of the Philosophy of Mind and Logic at University College London from 1946 until 1959, after which he returned to Oxford to become Wykeham Professor of Logic at New College.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He was president of the Aristotelian Society from 1951 to 1952 and knighted in 1970.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He was known for his advocacy of humanism, and was the second president of the British Humanist Association (now known as Humanists UK).
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer was born in St John's Wood, in north west London, to Jules Louis Cyprien Ayer and Reine (née Citroen), wealthy parents from continental Europe.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] His mother was from the Dutch-Jewish family that founded the Citroën car company in France; his father was a Swiss Calvinist financier who worked for the Rothschild family, including for their bank and as secretary to Alfred Rothschild.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer was educated at Ascham St Vincent's School, a former boarding preparatory school for boys in the seaside town of Eastbourne in Sussex, where he started boarding at the relatively early age of seven for reasons to do with the First World War, and at Eton College, where he was a King's Scholar.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] At Eton, Ayer first became known for his characteristic bravado and precocity.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Though primarily interested in his intellectual pursuits, he was very keen on sports, particularly rugby, and reputedly played the Eton Wall Game very well.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In the final examinations at Eton, Ayer came second in his year, and first in classics.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In his final year, as a member of Eton's senior council, he unsuccessfully campaigned for the abolition of corporal punishment at the school.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He won a classics scholarship to Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He graduated with a BA with first-class honours.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] After graduating from Oxford, Ayer spent a year in Vienna, returned to England and published his first book, *Language, Truth and Logic*, in 1936.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] This first exposition in English of logical positivism as newly developed by the Vienna Circle, made Ayer at age 26 the *enfant terrible* of British philosophy.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] As a newly famous intellectual, he played a prominent role in the Oxford by-election campaign of 1938.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer campaigned first for the Labour candidate Patrick Gordon Walker, and then for the joint Labour-Liberal "Independent Progressive" candidate Sandie Lindsay, who ran on an anti-appeasement platform against the Conservative candidate, Quintin Hogg, who ran as the appeasement candidate.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] The by-election, held on 27 October 1938, was quite close, with Hogg winning narrowly.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In the Second World War, Ayer served as an officer in the Welsh Guards, chiefly in intelligence (Special Operations Executive (SOE) and MI6).
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He was commissioned as a second lieutenant into the Welsh Guards from the Officer Cadet Training Unit on 21 September 1940.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] After the war, Ayer briefly returned to the University of Oxford where he became a fellow and Dean of Wadham College.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He then taught philosophy at University College London from 1946 until 1959, during which time he started to appear on radio and television.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He was an extrovert and social mixer who liked dancing and attending clubs in London and New York.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He was also obsessed with sport: he had played rugby for Eton, and was a noted cricketer and a keen supporter of Tottenham Hotspur football team, where he was for many years a season ticket holder.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] For an academic, Ayer was an unusually well-connected figure in his time, with close links to 'high society' and the establishment.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Presiding over Oxford high-tables, he is often described as charming, but could also be intimidating.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer was married four times to three women.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] His first marriage was from 1932 to 1941, to (Grace Isabel) Renée, with whom he had a son – allegedly the son of Ayer's friend and colleague Stuart Hampshire – and a daughter.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In 1960, Ayer married Alberta Constance (Dee) Wells, with whom he had one son.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] That marriage was dissolved in 1983, and the same year, Ayer married Vanessa Salmon, the former wife of politician Nigel Lawson.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] She died in 1985, and in 1989 Ayer remarried Wells, who survived him.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He also had a daughter with Hollywood columnist Sheilah Graham Westbrook.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In 1950, Ayer attended the founding meeting of the Congress for Cultural Freedom in West Berlin, though he later said he went only because of the offer of a "free trip".
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He gave a speech on why John Stuart Mill's conceptions of liberty and freedom were still valid in the 20th century.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Together with the historian Hugh Trevor-Roper, Ayer fought against Arthur Koestler and Franz Borkenau, arguing that they were far too dogmatic and extreme in their anti-communism, in fact proposing illiberal measures in the defence of liberty.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Adding to the tension was the location of the congress in West Berlin, together with the fact that the Korean War began on 25 June 1950, the fourth day of the congress, giving a feeling that the world was on the brink of war.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] From 1959 to his retirement in 1978, Ayer held the Wykeham Chair, Professor of Logic at Oxford.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] After his retirement, Ayer taught or lectured several times in the United States, including as a visiting professor at Bard College in 1987.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] At a party that same year held by fashion designer Fernando Sanchez, Ayer confronted Mike Tyson, who was forcing himself upon the then little-known model Naomi Campbell.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] When Ayer demanded that Tyson stop, Tyson reportedly asked, "Do you know who the fuck I am?
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] I'm the heavyweight champion of the world", to which Ayer replied, "And I am the former Wykeham Professor of Logic.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] I suggest that we talk about this like rational men".
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer and Tyson then began to talk, allowing Campbell to slip out.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Gully Wells, Ayer's stepdaughter via Dee Wells, records the same event with some slight variation of detail.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer was also involved in politics, including anti-Vietnam War activism, supporting the Labour Party (and later the Social Democratic Party), chairing the Campaign Against Racial Discrimination in Sport, and serving as president of the Homosexual Law Reform Society.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In 1978 he was interviewed for Bryan Magee's *Men of Ideas* television show, where he spoke about logical positivism and its legacy, later in 1987 he appeared on Magee's *The Great Philosophers* in an episode centering on Frege, Russell and Modern Logic.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In 1988, a year before his death, Ayer wrote an article titled "What I saw when I was dead", describing an unusual near-death experience after his heart stopped for four minutes as he choked on smoked salmon.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] From 1980 to 1989 he lived at 51 York Street, Marylebone, where a memorial plaque was unveiled on 19 November 1995.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In *Language, Truth and Logic* (1936), Ayer presents the verification principle as the only valid basis for philosophy.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Unless logical or empirical verification is possible, statements like "God exists" or "charity is good" are not true or untrue but meaningless, and may thus be excluded or ignored.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Religious language in particular is unverifiable and as such literally nonsense.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Mace's opinion that metaphysics is a form of intellectual poetry.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] The stance that a belief in God denotes no verifiable hypothesis is sometimes referred to as igtheism (for example, by Paul Kurtz).
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In later years, Ayer reiterated that he did not believe in God and began to call himself an atheist.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He followed in the footsteps of Bertrand Russell by debating religion with the Jesuit scholar Frederick Copleston.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He focuses on propositions of the first class – moral judgements – saying that those of the second class belong to science, those of the third are mere commands, and those of the fourth (which are considered normative ethics as opposed to meta-ethics) are too concrete for ethical philosophy.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer argues that moral judgements cannot be translated into non-ethical, empirical terms and thus cannot be verified; in this he agrees with ethical intuitionists.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] But he differs from intuitionists by discarding appeals to intuition of non-empirical moral truths as "worthless" since the intuition of one person often contradicts that of another.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Between 1945 and 1947, together with Russell and George Orwell, Ayer contributed a series of articles to *Polemic*, a short-lived British *Magazine of Philosophy, Psychology, and Aesthetics* edited by the ex-Communist Humphrey Slater.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer was closely associated with the British humanist movement.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He was an Honorary Associate of the Rationalist Press Association from 1947 until his death.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1963.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In 1965, he became the first president of the Agnostics' Adoption Society and in the same year succeeded Julian Huxley as president of the British Humanist Association, a post he held until 1970.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In 1968 he edited *The Humanist Outlook*, a collection of essays on the meaning of humanism.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He was one of the signers of the Humanist Manifesto.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer is best known for popularising the verification principle, in particular through his presentation of it in *Language, Truth, and Logic*.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] The principle was at the time at the heart of the debates of the so-called Vienna Circle, which Ayer had visited as a young guest.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Others, including the circle's leading light, Moritz Schlick, were already writing papers on the issue.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer's formulation was that a sentence can be meaningful only if it has verifiable empirical import; otherwise, it is either "analytical" if tautologous or "metaphysical" (i.e. meaningless, or "literally senseless").
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He started to work on the book at the age of 23 and it was published when he was 26.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer's philosophical ideas were deeply influenced by those of the Vienna Circle and David Hume.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] His clear, vibrant and polemical exposition of them makes *Language, Truth and Logic* essential reading on the tenets of logical empiricism; the book is regarded as a classic of 20th-century analytic philosophy and is widely read in philosophy courses around the world.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer wrote two books on the philosopher Bertrand Russell, *Russell and Moore: The Analytic Heritage* (1971) and *Russell* (1972).
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He also wrote an introductory book on the philosophy of David Hume and a short biography of Voltaire.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer was a strong critic of the German philosopher Martin Heidegger.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] As a logical positivist, Ayer was in conflict with Heidegger's vast, overarching theories of existence.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer considered them completely unverifiable through empirical demonstration and logical analysis, and this sort of philosophy an unfortunate strain in modern thought.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He considered Heidegger the worst example of such philosophy, which Ayer believed entirely useless.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In *Philosophy in the Twentieth Century*, Ayer accuses Heidegger of "surprising ignorance" or "unscrupulous distortion" and "what can fairly be described as charlatanism".
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In 1972–73, Ayer gave the Gifford Lectures at the University of St Andrews, later published as *The Central Questions of Philosophy*.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] He still believed in the viewpoint he shared with the logical positivists: that large parts of what was traditionally called philosophy—including metaphysics, theology and aesthetics—were not matters that could be judged true or false, and that it was thus meaningless to discuss them.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] In *The Concept of a Person and Other Essays* (1963), Ayer heavily criticised Wittgenstein's private language argument.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer's sense-data theory in *Foundations of Empirical Knowledge* was famously criticised by fellow Oxonian J.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Austin in *Sense and Sensibilia*, a landmark 1950s work of ordinary language philosophy.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer responded in the essay "Has Austin Refuted the Sense-datum Theory?", which can be found in his *Metaphysics and Common Sense* (1969).
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer was awarded a knighthood as Knight Bachelor in the London Gazette on 1 January 1970.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] Ayer's biographer, Ben Rogers, deposited 7 boxes of research material accumulated through the writing process at University College London in 2007.
[src:ambiguity/a-j-ayer] The material was donated in collaboration with Ayer's family.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] An **abbreviation** (from Latin **brevis** 'short') is a shortened form of a word or phrase, by any method including shortening, contraction, initialism (which includes acronym), or crasis.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] An abbreviation may be a shortened form of a word, usually ended with a trailing full stop (period).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] For example, the term *etc.* is the usual abbreviation for the Latin phrase *et cetera*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] A *contraction* is an abbreviation formed by leaving out letters or sounds, typically replaced by an apostrophe in English.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Examples include *I'm* for *I am* and *li'l* for *little*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] An *initialism* or *acronym* is an abbreviation consisting of the initial letter of a sequence of words without other punctuation.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] For example, FBI (/ˌɛf.biːˈaɪ/), USA (/ˌjuː.ɛsˈeɪ/), IBM (/ˌaɪ.biːˈɛm/), BBC (/ˌbiː.biːˈsiː/).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] When initialism is used as the preferred term, acronym refers more specifically to when the abbreviation is pronounced as a word rather than as separate letters; examples include SWAT and NASA.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Initialisms, contractions and crasis share some semantic and phonetic functions, and are connected by the term *abbreviation* in loose parlance.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In early times, abbreviations may have been common due to the effort involved in writing (many inscriptions were carved in stone) or to provide secrecy via obfuscation.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Reduction of a word to a single letter was common in both Greek and Roman writing.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In Roman inscriptions, "Words were commonly abbreviated by using the initial letter or letters of words, and most inscriptions have at least one abbreviation".
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] However, "some could have more than one meaning, depending on their context.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Abbreviations were frequently used in early English.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Manuscripts of copies of the Old English poem *Beowulf* used many abbreviations, for example the Tironian et (⁊) or & for *and*, and y for *since*, so that "not much space is wasted".
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The standardisation of English in the 15th through 17th centuries included a growth in the use of such abbreviations.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] At first, abbreviations were sometimes represented with various suspension signs, not only periods.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] For example, sequences like ⟨er⟩ were replaced with ⟨ɔ⟩, as in mastɔ for *master* and exacɔbate for *exacerbate*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] While this may seem trivial, it was symptomatic of an attempt by people manually reproducing academic texts to reduce the copy time.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] — Warden of Merton College, University of Oxford in *Registrum Annalium Collegii Mertonensis*, 1503.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In the Early Modern English period, between the 15th and 17th centuries, the thorn Þ was used for *th*, as in Þe ('the').
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In modern times, ⟨Þ⟩ was often used (in the form ⟨y⟩) for promotional reasons, as in Ye Olde Tea Shoppe.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] During the growth of philological linguistic theory in academic Britain, abbreviating became very fashionable.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Likewise, a century earlier in Boston, a fad of abbreviation started that swept the United States, with the globally popular term OK generally credited as a remnant of its influence.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Over the years, however, the lack of convention in some style guides has made it difficult to determine which two-word abbreviations should be abbreviated with periods and which should not.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Widespread use of electronic communication through mobile phones and the Internet during the 1990s led to a marked rise in colloquial abbreviation.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] This was due largely to increasing popularity of textual communication services such as instant and text messaging.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The original SMS supported message lengths of 160 characters at most (using the GSM 03.38 character set), for instance.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] This brevity gave rise to an informal abbreviation scheme sometimes called Textese, with which 10% or more of the words in a typical SMS message are abbreviated.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] More recently Twitter, a popular social networking service, began driving abbreviation use with 140 character message limits.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In HTML, abbreviations can be annotated using a dedicated tag: `<abbr title="Editor">Ed.</abbr>` In this example, the meaning of "Ed." as "Editor" is revealed by hovering the cursor over it.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In modern English, there are multiple conventions for abbreviation, and there is controversy as to which should be used.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] One generally accepted rule is to be consistent in a body of work.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] To this end, publishers may express their preferences in a style guide.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Some controversies that arise are described below.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] If the original word was capitalized then the first letter of its abbreviation should retain the capital, for example Lev. for *Leviticus*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] When a word is abbreviated to more than a single letter and was originally spelled with lower case letters then there is no need for capitalization.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] However, when abbreviating a phrase where only the first letter of each word is taken, then all letters should be capitalized, as in YTD for *year-to-date*, PCB for *printed circuit board* and FYI for *for your information*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] However, see the following section regarding abbreviations that have become common vocabulary: these are no longer written with capital letters.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] A period (full stop) is sometimes used to signify abbreviation, but opinion is divided as to when and if this convention is best practice.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] According to Hart's Rules, a word shortened by dropping letters from the end terminates with a full stop (period), whereas a word shorted by dropping letters from the middle does not.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Fowler's Modern English Usage says a full stop (period) is used for both of these shortened forms, but recommends against this practice.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] It advises it only for end-shortened words and lower-case initialisms, not for middle-shortened words and upper-case initialisms.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Some British style guides, such as for The Guardian and The Economist, disallow periods for all abbreviations.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In American English, the period is usually included regardless of whether or not it is a contraction, e.g.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] *Dr.* or *Mrs.* In some cases, periods are optional, as in either *US* or *U.S.* for *United States*, *EU* or *E.U.* for *European Union*, and *UN* or *U.N.* for *United Nations*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] There are some house styles, however—American ones included—that remove the periods from almost all abbreviations.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Acronyms that were originally capitalized (with or without periods) but have since entered the vocabulary as generic words are no longer written with capital letters nor with any periods.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Examples are sonar, radar, lidar, laser, snafu, and scuba.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In the past, some initialisms were styled with a period after each letter and a space between each pair.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] There are multiple ways to pluralize an abbreviation.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Sometimes this accomplished by adding an apostrophe and an *s* ('s), as in "two PC's have broken screens".
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] But, some find this confusing since the notation can indicate possessive case.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] And, this style is deprecated by many style guides.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] For instance, Kate Turabian, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] For example, "DVDs" and "URLs" and "Ph.D.'s", while the Modern Language Association explicitly says, "do not use an apostrophe to form the plural of an abbreviation".
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Also, the American Psychological Association specifically says, "without an apostrophe".
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] However, the 1999 style guide for *The New York Times* states that the addition of an apostrophe is necessary when pluralizing all abbreviations, preferring "PC's, TV's and VCR's".
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Forming a plural of an initialization without an apostrophe can also be used for a number, or a letter.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] For units of measure, the same form is used for both singular and plural.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] When an abbreviation contains more than one period, *Hart's Rules* recommends putting the *s* after the final one.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] According to *Hart's Rules*, an apostrophe may be used in rare cases where clarity calls for it, for example when letters or symbols are referred to as objects.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In Latin, and continuing to the derivative forms in European languages as well as English, single-letter abbreviations had the plural being a doubling of the letter for note-taking.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Most of these deal with writing and publishing.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] A few longer abbreviations use this as well.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Publications based in the U.S. tend to follow the style guides of *The Chicago Manual of Style* and the Associated Press.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The U.S. government follows a style guide published by the U.S.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The National Institute of Standards and Technology sets the style for abbreviations of units.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Writers often use shorthand to denote units of measure.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Such shorthand can be an abbreviation, such as "in" for "inch" or can be a symbol such as "km" for "kilometre".
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In the International System of Units (SI) manual the word "symbol" is used consistently to define the shorthand used to represent the various SI units of measure.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] A syllabic abbreviation is usually formed from the initial syllables of several words, such as *Interpol* = *International* + *police*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are usually written using lower case, sometimes starting with a capital letter, and are always pronounced as words rather than letter by letter.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations should be distinguished from portmanteaus, which combine two words without necessarily taking whole syllables from each.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are not widely used in English.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Some UK government agencies such as Ofcom (Office of Communications) and the former Oftel (Office of Telecommunications) use this style.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] New York City has various neighborhoods named by syllabic abbreviation, such as Tribeca (Triangle below Canal Street) and SoHo (South of Houston Street).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] This usage has spread into other American cities, giving SoMa, San Francisco (South of Market), and LoDo, Denver (Lower Downtown), amongst others.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Sections of California are also often colloquially syllabically abbreviated, as in NorCal (Northern California), CenCal (Central California), and SoCal (Southern California).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Additionally, in the context of Los Angeles, the syllabic abbreviation SoHo (Southern Hollywood) refers to the southern portion of the Hollywood neighborhood.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Partially syllabic abbreviations are preferred by the US Navy, as they increase readability amidst the large number of initialisms that would otherwise have to fit into the same acronyms.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Hence *DESRON 6* is used (in the full capital form) to mean "Destroyer Squadron 6", while *COMNAVAIRLANT* would be "Commander, Naval Air Force (in the) Atlantic".
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are a prominent feature of Newspeak, the fictional language of George Orwell's dystopian novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The political contractions of Newspeak—*Ingsoc* (English Socialism), *Minitrue* (Ministry of Truth), *Miniplenty* (Ministry of Plenty)—are described by Orwell as similar to real examples of German *(see below)* and Russian (*see below)* contractions in the 20th century.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The contractions in Newspeak are supposed to have a political function by virtue of their abbreviated structure itself: nice sounding and easily pronounceable, their purpose is to mask all ideological content from the speaker.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] A more recent syllabic abbreviation has emerged with the disease COVID-19 (Corona Virus Disease 2019) caused by the Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (itself frequently abbreviated to SARS-CoV-2, partly an initialism).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In Albanian, syllabic acronyms are sometimes used for composing a person's name, such as *Migjeni*—an abbreviation from his original name (*Millosh Gjergj Nikolla*) a famous Albanian poet and writer—or *ASDRENI* (*Aleksander Stavre Drenova*), another famous Albanian poet.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Other such names which are used commonly in recent decades are GETOAR, composed from *Gegeria* + *Tosks* (representing the two main dialects of the Albanian language, Gegë and Toskë), and *Arbanon*—which is an alternative way used to describe all Albanian lands.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations were and are common in German; much like acronyms in English, they have a distinctly modern connotation, although contrary to popular belief, many date back to before 1933, if not the end of the Great War.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] *Kriminalpolizei*, literally *criminal police* but idiomatically the Criminal Investigation Department of any German police force, begat *KriPo* (variously capitalised), and likewise *Schutzpolizei* (*protection police* or *uniform department*) begat *SchuPo*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Along the same lines, the Swiss Federal Railways' Transit Police—the *Transportpolizei*—are abbreviated as the *TraPo*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] With the National Socialist German Workers' Party gaining power came a frenzy of government reorganisation, and with it a series of entirely new syllabic abbreviations.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Non regime-aligned partially syllabic abbreviations also existed like "Gröfaz" for the self-proclaimed "größter Feldherr aller Zeiten" (greatest military commander of all time), i.e.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The new order of the German Democratic Republic in the east brought about a conscious denazification, but also a repudiation of earlier turns of phrase in favour of neologisms such as *Stasi* for *Staatssicherheit* ("state security", the secret police) and *VoPo* for *Volkspolizei*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The phrase *politisches Büro*, which may be rendered literally as "office of politics" or idiomatically as "political party steering committee", became *Politbüro*.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are not only used in politics, however.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are very common in Russian, Belarusian and Ukrainian.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] They are often used as names of organizations.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Historically, popularization of abbreviations was a way to simplify mass-education in 1920s (see Likbez).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The word *kolkhoz* (*kollektívnoye khozyáystvo*, collective farm) is another example.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Leninist organisations such as the *Comintern* (*Communist International*) and *Komsomol* (*Kommunisticheskii Soyuz Molodyozhi*, or "Communist youth union") used Russian language syllabic abbreviations.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In the modern Russian language, words like *Rosselkhozbank* (from Rossiysky selskokhozyaystvenny bank — Russian Agricultural Bank, RusAg) and *Minobrnauki* (from Ministerstvo obrazovaniya i nauki — Ministry of Education and Science) are still commonly used.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] In nearby Belarus, there are *Beltelecom* (Belarus Telecommunication) and Belsat (Belarus Satellite).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are common in Spanish; examples abound in organization names such as Pemex for *Petróleos Mexicanos* ("Mexican Petroleums") or Fonafifo for *Fondo Nacional de Financimiento Forestal* (National Forestry Financing Fund).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] ("Banamex"), Teléfonos de México, S.A.B. de C.V.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] ("TELMEX"), Operadora de Cinemas, S.A. de C.V.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Malaysian abbreviation often uses letters from each word, while Indonesia usually uses syllables; although some cases do not follow the style.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] For example, general elections in Malaysian Malay often shortened into PRU (**p**ilihan **r**aya **u**mum) while Indonesian often shortened into pemilu (**pemil**ihan **u**mum).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Another example is Ministry of Health in which Malaysian Malay uses KKM (**K**ementerian **K**esihatan **M**alaysia), compared to Indonesian Kemenkes (**Kemen**terian **Kes**ehatan).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] East Asian languages whose writing systems use Chinese characters form abbreviations similarly by using key Chinese characters from a term or phrase.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] For example, in Japanese the term for the United Nations, *kokusai rengō* (国際連合) is often abbreviated to *kokuren* (国連).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] (Such abbreviations are called ryakugo (略語) in Japanese; see also Japanese abbreviated and contracted words).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The syllabic abbreviation of kanji words is frequently used for universities: for instance, *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō daigaku* (東京大学, University of Tokyo) and is used similarly in Chinese: *Běidà* (北大) for *Běijīng Dàxué* (北京大学, Peking University).
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] Korean universities often follow the same conventions, such as *Hongdae* (홍대) as short for *Hongik Daehakgyo*, or Hongik University.
[src:ambiguity/abbreviation] The English phrase "Gung ho" originated as a Chinese abbreviation.
[src:ambiguity/accident-fallacy] The fallacy of **accident** (also called **destroying the exception** or ***a dicto simpliciter ad dictum secundum quid***) is an informal fallacy where a general rule is applied to an exceptional case.
[src:ambiguity/accident-fallacy] The fallacy of accident gets its name from the fact that one or more accidental features of the specific case make it an exception to the rule.
[src:ambiguity/accident-fallacy] A generalization that is largely true may not apply in a specific case (or to some subcategory of cases) for good reasons.
[src:ambiguity/accident-fallacy] It is one of the thirteen fallacies originally identified by Aristotle in *Sophistical Refutations*.
[src:ambiguity/accident-fallacy] Surgeons are people who cut other people with knives.
[src:ambiguity/accident-fallacy] The argument is committing the fallacy of accident because it erroneously generalizes a specific characteristic of cutting people with knives (which is a crime when done outside the context of certain professions or situations) to all instances of cutting people with knives.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] A combination of both precision and trueness, accounting for the two types of observational error (random and systematic), so that high accuracy requires both high precision and high trueness.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] This usage corresponds to ISO's definition of *accuracy* (trueness and precision).
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In the fields of science and engineering, the accuracy of a measurement system is the degree of closeness of measurements of a quantity to that quantity's true value.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] The precision of a measurement system, related to reproducibility and repeatability, is the degree to which repeated measurements under unchanged conditions show the same results.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Although the two words precision and accuracy can be synonymous in colloquial use, they are deliberately contrasted in the context of the scientific method.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] The field of statistics, where the interpretation of measurements plays a central role, prefers to use the terms *bias* and *variability* instead of accuracy and precision: bias is the amount of inaccuracy and variability is the amount of imprecision.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] A measurement system can be accurate but not precise, precise but not accurate, neither, or both.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] For example, if an experiment contains a systematic error, then increasing the sample size generally increases precision but does not improve accuracy.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] The result would be a consistent yet inaccurate string of results from the flawed experiment.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Eliminating the systematic error improves accuracy but does not change precision.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] A measurement system is considered *valid* if it is both *accurate* and *precise*.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Related terms include *bias* (non-random or directed effects caused by a factor or factors unrelated to the independent variable) and *error* (random variability).
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] The terminology is also applied to indirect measurements—that is, values obtained by a computational procedure from observed data.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In addition to accuracy and precision, measurements may also have a measurement resolution, which is the smallest change in the underlying physical quantity that produces a response in the measurement.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In numerical analysis, accuracy is also the nearness of a calculation to the true value; while precision is the resolution of the representation, typically defined by the number of decimal or binary digits.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In military terms, accuracy refers primarily to the accuracy of fire (*justesse de tir*), the precision of fire expressed by the closeness of a grouping of shots at and around the centre of the target.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] A shift in the meaning of these terms appeared with the publication of the ISO 5725 series of standards in 1994, which is also reflected in the 2008 issue of the BIPM International Vocabulary of Metrology (VIM), items 2.13 and 2.14.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] According to ISO 5725-1, the general term "accuracy" is used to describe the closeness of a measurement to the true value.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] When the term is applied to sets of measurements of the same measurand, it involves a component of random error and a component of systematic error.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In this case trueness is the closeness of the mean of a set of measurement results to the actual (true) value, that is the systematic error, and precision is the closeness of agreement among a set of results, that is the random error.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] ISO 5725-1 and VIM also avoid the use of the term "bias", previously specified in BS 5497-1, because it has different connotations outside the fields of science and engineering, as in medicine and law.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In industrial instrumentation, accuracy is the measurement tolerance, or transmission of the instrument and defines the limits of the errors made when the instrument is used in normal operating conditions.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Ideally a measurement device is both accurate and precise, with measurements all close to and tightly clustered around the true value.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] The accuracy and precision of a measurement process is usually established by repeatedly measuring some traceable reference standard.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Such standards are defined in the International System of Units (abbreviated SI from French: *Système international d'unités*) and maintained by national standards organizations such as the National Institute of Standards and Technology in the United States.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] This also applies when measurements are repeated and averaged.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In that case, the term standard error is properly applied: the precision of the average is equal to the known standard deviation of the process divided by the square root of the number of measurements averaged.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Further, the central limit theorem shows that the probability distribution of the averaged measurements will be closer to a normal distribution than that of individual measurements.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] A common convention in science and engineering is to express accuracy and/or precision implicitly by means of significant figures.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Where not explicitly stated, the margin of error is understood to be one-half the value of the last significant place.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] For instance, a recording of 843.6 m, or 843.0 m, or 800.0 m would imply a margin of 0.05 m (the last significant place is the tenths place), while a recording of 843 m would imply a margin of error of 0.5 m (the last significant digits are the units).
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] A reading of 8,000 m, with trailing zeros and no decimal point, is ambiguous; the trailing zeros may or may not be intended as significant figures.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] To avoid this ambiguity, the number could be represented in scientific notation: 8.0 × 103 m indicates that the first zero is significant (hence a margin of 50 m) while 8.000 × 103 m indicates that all three zeros are significant, giving a margin of 0.5 m.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Similarly, one can use a multiple of the basic measurement unit: 8.0 km is equivalent to 8.0 × 103 m.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] It indicates a margin of 0.05 km (50 m).
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] However, reliance on this convention can lead to false precision errors when accepting data from sources that do not obey it.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] For example, a source reporting a number like 153,753 with precision +/- 5,000 looks like it has precision +/- 0.5.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Under the convention it would have been rounded to 150,000.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Alternatively, in a scientific context, if it is desired to indicate the margin of error with more precision, one can use a notation such as 7.54398(23) × 10−10 m, meaning a range of between 7.54375 and 7.54421 × 10−10 m.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In engineering, precision is often taken as three times Standard Deviation of measurements taken, representing the range that 99.73% of measurements can occur within.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] For example, an ergonomist measuring the human body can be confident that 99.73% of their extracted measurements fall within ± 0.7 cm - if using the GRYPHON processing system - or ± 13 cm - if using unprocessed data.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In this context, the concepts of trueness and precision as defined by ISO 5725-1 are not applicable.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] One reason is that there is not a single “true value” of a quantity, but rather two possible true values for every case, while accuracy is an average across all cases and therefore takes into account both values.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] However, the term *precision* is used in this context to mean a different metric originating from the field of information retrieval (see § In information systems).
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] When computing accuracy in multiclass classification, accuracy is simply the fraction of correct classifications: ${\text{Accuracy}}={\frac {\text{correct classifications}}{\text{all classifications}}}$ This is usually expressed as a percentage.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] For example, if a classifier makes ten predictions and nine of them are correct, the accuracy is 90%.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Accuracy is sometimes also viewed as a *micro metric*, to underline that it tends to be greatly affected by the particular class prevalence in a dataset and the classifier's biases.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Furthermore, it is also called top-1 accuracy to distinguish it from top-5 accuracy, common in convolutional neural network evaluation.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] To evaluate top-5 accuracy, the classifier must provide relative likelihoods for each class.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] When these are sorted, a classification is considered correct if the correct classification falls anywhere within the top 5 predictions made by the network.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Top-5 accuracy was popularized by the ImageNet challenge.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] It is usually higher than top-1 accuracy, as any correct predictions in the 2nd through 5th positions will not improve the top-1 score, but do improve the top-5 score.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In psychometrics and psychophysics, the term *accuracy* is interchangeably used with validity and *constant error*.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] *Precision* is a synonym for reliability and *variable error*.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] The validity of a measurement instrument or psychological test is established through experiment or correlation with behavior.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Reliability is established with a variety of statistical techniques, classically through an internal consistency test like Cronbach's alpha to ensure sets of related questions have related responses, and then comparison of those related question between reference and target population.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In logic simulation, a common mistake in evaluation of accurate models is to compare a logic simulation model to a transistor circuit simulation model.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] This is a comparison of differences in precision, not accuracy.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Precision is measured with respect to detail and accuracy is measured with respect to reality.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Commonly used metrics include the notions of precision and recall.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In this context, precision is defined as the fraction of documents correctly retrieved compared to the documents retrieved (true positives divided by true positives plus false positives), using a set of ground truth relevant results selected by humans.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Recall is defined as the fraction of documents correctly retrieved compared to the relevant documents (true positives divided by true positives plus false negatives).
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Less commonly, the metric of accuracy is used, is defined as the fraction of documents correctly classified compared to the documents (true positives plus true negatives divided by true positives plus true negatives plus false positives plus false negatives).
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] None of these metrics take into account the ranking of results.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Ranking is very important for web search engines because readers seldom go past the first page of results, and there are too many documents on the web to manually classify all of them as to whether they should be included or excluded from a given search.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Adding a cutoff at a particular number of results takes ranking into account to some degree.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] The measure precision at k, for example, is a measure of precision looking only at the top ten (k=10) search results.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] More sophisticated metrics, such as discounted cumulative gain, take into account each individual ranking, and are more commonly used where this is important.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] In cognitive systems, accuracy and precision is used to characterize and measure results of a cognitive process performed by biological or artificial entities where a cognitive process is a transformation of data, information, knowledge, or wisdom to a higher-valued form.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] (DIKW Pyramid) Sometimes, a cognitive process produces exactly the intended or desired output but sometimes produces output far from the intended or desired.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] Furthermore, repetitions of a cognitive process do not always produce the same output.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] *Cognitive accuracy* (CA) is the propensity of a cognitive process to produce the intended or desired output.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] *Cognitive precision* (CP) is the propensity of a cognitive process to produce the same output.
[src:ambiguity/accuracy-and-precision] To measure augmented cognition in human/cog ensembles, where one or more humans work collaboratively with one or more cognitive systems (cogs), increases in cognitive accuracy and cognitive precision assist in measuring the degree of cognitive augmentation.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Other uses of the term *ad hominem* are more traditional, referring to arguments tailored to fit a particular audience, and may be encountered in specialized philosophical usage.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] These typically refer to the dialectical strategy of using the target's own beliefs and arguments against them, while not agreeing with the validity of those beliefs and arguments.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] *Ad hominem* arguments were first studied in ancient Greece; John Locke revived the examination of *ad hominem* arguments in the 17th century.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] A common misconception is that an *ad hominem* attack is synonymous with an insult.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] This is not true, although some *ad hominem* arguments may be considered insulting by the recipient.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] The various types of *ad hominem* arguments have been known in the West since at least the ancient Greeks.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Aristotle, in his work *Sophistical Refutations*, detailed the fallaciousness of putting the questioner but not the argument under scrutiny.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] His description was somewhat different from the modern understanding, referring to a class of sophistry that applies an ambiguously worded question about people to a specific person.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] The proper refutation, he wrote, is not to debate the attributes of the person (*solutio ad hominem*) but to address the original ambiguity.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Many examples of ancient non-fallacious *ad hominem* arguments are preserved in the works of the Pyrrhonist philosopher Sextus Empiricus.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] In these arguments, the concepts and assumptions of the opponents are used as part of a dialectical strategy against them to demonstrate the unsoundness of their own arguments and assumptions.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] In this way, the arguments are to the person (*ad hominem*), but without attacking the properties of the individuals making the arguments.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] This kind of argument is also known as "argument from commitment".
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Italian Galileo Galilei and British philosopher John Locke also examined the argument from commitment, a form of the *ad hominem* argument, meaning examining an argument on the basis of whether it stands true to the principles of the person carrying the argument.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] In the mid-19th century, the modern understanding of the term *ad hominem* started to take shape, with the broad definition given by English logician Richard Whately.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] According to Whately, *ad hominem* arguments were "addressed to the peculiar circumstances, character, avowed opinions, or past conduct of the individual".
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Over time, the term acquired a different meaning; by the beginning of the 20th century, it was linked to a logical fallacy, in which a debater, instead of disproving an argument, attacked their opponent.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] This approach was also popularized in philosophical textbooks of the mid-20th century, and it was challenged by Australian philosopher Charles Leonard Hamblin in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] In a detailed work, he suggested that the inclusion of a statement against a person in an argument does not necessarily make it a fallacious argument since that particular phrase is not a premise that leads to a conclusion.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] While Hamblin's criticism was not widely accepted, Canadian philosopher Douglas N.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Walton examined the fallaciousness of the *ad hominem* argument further.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Except in specialized philosophical discourse, contemporary use of the term *ad hominem* describes a direct attack on the character and ethos of a person, in an attempt to refute their argument.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] The Latin phrase *argumentum ad hominem* stands for 'argument against the person'.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] In this context, *ad* means 'against', but could also mean 'to' or 'towards'.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] The terms *ad mulierem* and *ad feminam* have been used specifically when the person receiving the criticism is female but the term *hominem* (accusative of *homo*) is gender-neutral in Latin, and merely implies that the recipient of the insult is a human being.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Fallacious *ad hominem* reasoning is categorized among informal fallacies, more precisely as a genetic fallacy, a subcategory of fallacies of irrelevance.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Canadian philosopher Christopher Tindale approaches somewhat different the *tu quoque* fallacy.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] According to Tindale, a *tu quoque* fallacy appears when a response to an argument is made on the history of the arguer.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] This argument is also invalid because it does not disprove the premise; if the premise is true, then source A may be a hypocrite or even changed their mind, but this does not make the statement less credible from a logical perspective.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] A common example, given by Tindale, is when a doctor advises a patient to lose weight, but the patient argues that there is no need for him to go on a diet because the doctor is also overweight.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Circumstantial *ad hominem* points out that someone is in circumstances (for instance, their job, wealth, property, or relations) such that they are disposed to take a particular position.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] It constitutes an attack on the bias of a source.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] As with other types of the argument, the circumstantial *ad hominem* could be fallacious or not.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] It could be fallacious because a disposition to make a certain argument does not make the argument invalid; this overlaps with the genetic fallacy (an argument that a claim is incorrect due to its source).
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] But it also may be a sound argument, if the premises are correct and the bias is relevant to the argument.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] A simple example is: a father may tell his daughter not to start smoking because she will damage her health, and she may point out that he is or was a smoker.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] This does not alter the fact that smoking might cause various diseases.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Her father's inconsistency is not a proper reason to reject his claim.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Walton, philosopher and pundit on informal fallacies, argues that a circumstantial *ad hominem* argument can be non-fallacious.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] This could be the case when someone (A) attacks the personality of another person (B), making an argument (a) while the personality of B is relevant to argument *a*, i.e.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] To illustrate this reasoning, Walton gives the example of a witness at a trial: if he had been caught lying and cheating in his own life, should the jury take his word for granted?
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Individual S is also associated with Group G, who has an unfavorable reputation.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Therefore, individual S and his views are questionable.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Academic Leigh Kolb gives as an example that the 2008 US vice-presidential candidate Sarah Palin attacked Barack Obama for having worked with Bill Ayers, who had been a leader in the Weather Underground terrorist group in the 1960s.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Despite Obama denouncing every act of terrorism, his opponents still associated him with terrorism.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Guilt by association is frequently found in social and political debates.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] It also appears after major events (such as scandals and terrorism) linked to a specific group.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Kolb cites the peak of attacks against Muslims in the US after the September 11 attacks.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Abusive *ad hominem* argument (or direct *ad hominem*) is associated with an attack to the character of the person carrying an argument.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] This kind of argument, besides usually being fallacious, is also counterproductive, as a proper dialogue is hard to achieve after such an attack.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Key issues in examining an argument to determine whether it is an *ad hominem* fallacy or not are whether the accusation against the person stands true or not, and whether the accusation is relevant to the argument.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] An example is a dialogue at the court, where the attorney cross-examines an eyewitness, bringing to light the fact that the witness was convicted in the past for lying.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] If the attorney's conclusion is that the witness is lying, that would be wrong.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] But if his argument would be that the witness should not be trusted, that would not be a fallacy.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] This usage is generally only encountered in specialist philosophical usage or in pre-20th century usages.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] This type of argument is also known as the *ex concessis* argument (Latin for 'from what has been conceded already').
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Author Eithan Orkibi, having studied Israeli politics prior to elections, described two other forms of *ad hominem* attacks that are common during election periods.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] They both depend on the collective memory shared by both proponents and the audience.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] The first is the "precedent *ad hominem*", according to which the previous history of someone means that they do not fit for the office.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] It goes like this: "My opponent was (allegedly) wrong in the past, therefore he is wrong now".
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] The second one is a behavioral *ad hominem*: "my opponent was not decent in his arguments in the past, so he is not now either".
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] These kinds of attacks are based on the inability of the audience to have a clear view of the amount of false statements by both parts of the debate.
[src:ambiguity/ad-hominem] Walton has argued that *ad hominem* reasoning is not always fallacious, and that in some instances, questions of personal conduct, character, motives, etc., are legitimate and relevant to the issue, as when it directly involves hypocrisy, or actions contradicting the subject's words.
[src:ambiguity/ad-nauseam] The fallacy of dragging the conversation to an *ad nauseam* state in order to then assert one's position as correct due to it not having been contradicted is also called ****argumentum ad infinitum**** (to infinity) and **argument from repetition**.
[src:ambiguity/ad-nauseam] The term is defined by the *American Heritage Dictionary* as "to a disgusting or ridiculous degree; to the point of nausea".
[src:ambiguity/ad-nauseam] Colloquially, it is sometimes used as "until nobody cares to discuss it any more".
[src:ambiguity/affirmative-conclusion-from-a-negative-premise] An **affirmative conclusion from a negative premise,** or an **illicit negative,** is a formal fallacy that is committed when a categorical syllogism has a positive conclusion and one or two negative premises.
[src:ambiguity/affirmative-conclusion-from-a-negative-premise] No fish are dogs, and no dogs can fly, therefore all fish can fly.
[src:ambiguity/affirmative-conclusion-from-a-negative-premise] The only thing that can be properly inferred from these premises is that some things that are not fish cannot fly, provided that dogs exist.
[src:ambiguity/affirmative-conclusion-from-a-negative-premise] People who read that trash don't appreciate real literature.
[src:ambiguity/affirmative-conclusion-from-a-negative-premise] Therefore, we appreciate real literature.
[src:ambiguity/affirmative-conclusion-from-a-negative-premise] It is a fallacy because any valid forms of categorical syllogism that assert a negative premise must have a negative conclusion.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] An outcome of ambiguity is uncertainty, but uncertainty itself refers to a state in which outcomes or meanings are known but their likelihood, stability, or implications cannot be reliably assessed.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Ambiguity is not simply the absence of information.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] It is the lack of meaning and direction caused by insufficient context and unclear framing, which obstructs the ability to determine what counts as a valid interpretation or resolution.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The prefix ambi- reflects the idea of “two” or “multiple,” as in multiple possible meanings.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The concept of ambiguity is generally contrasted with vagueness.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In ambiguity, multiple distinct interpretations compete because the frame of meaning is unclear and is shaped by personal history and mental models.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] With vagueness, in contrast, the general interpretation is often understood, but the boundaries are fuzzy, so it is difficult to specify the meaning at the desired level of precision.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Lexical ambiguity is contrasted with semantic ambiguity.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The former represents a choice between a finite number of known and meaningful context-dependent interpretations.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The latter represents a choice between any number of possible interpretations, none of which may have a standard agreed-upon meaning.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] This form of ambiguity is closely related to vagueness.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Ambiguity in human language is argued to reflect principles of efficient communication.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Languages that communicate efficiently will avoid sending information that is redundant with information provided in the context.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] This can be shown mathematically to result in a system that is ambiguous when context is neglected.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In this way, ambiguity is viewed as a generally useful feature of a linguistic system.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Linguistic ambiguity can be a problem in law, because the interpretation of written documents and oral agreements is often of paramount importance.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The lexical ambiguity of a word or phrase applies to it having more than one meaning in the language to which the word belongs.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] "Meaning" here refers to whatever should be represented by a good dictionary.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] For instance, the word "bank" has several distinct lexical definitions, including "financial institution" and "edge of a river".
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] One could say, "I bought herbs from the apothecary".
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] This could mean one actually spoke to the apothecary (pharmacist) or went to the apothecary (pharmacy).
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The context in which an ambiguous word is used often makes it clearer which of the meanings is intended.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] If, for instance, someone says, "I put $100 in the bank", most people would not think someone used a shovel to dig in the mud.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] However, some linguistic contexts do not provide sufficient information to make a used word clearer.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Lexical ambiguity can be addressed by algorithmic methods that automatically associate the appropriate meaning with a word in context, a task referred to as word-sense disambiguation.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The use of multi-defined words requires the author or speaker to clarify their context and sometimes elaborate on their specific intended meaning (in which case, a less ambiguous term should have been used).
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The goal of clear, concise communication is that the receiver(s) have no misunderstanding about what was meant to be conveyed.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] An exception to this could include a politician whose "weasel words" and obfuscation are necessary to gain support from multiple constituents with mutually exclusive conflicting desires from their candidate of choice.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Ambiguity is a powerful tool of political science.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] More problematic are words whose multiple meanings express closely related concepts.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] "Good", for example, can mean "useful" or "functional" (*That's a good hammer*), "exemplary" (*She's a good student*), "pleasing" (*This is good soup*), "moral" (*a good person* versus *the lesson to be learned from a story*), "righteous", etc.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] "I have a good daughter" is not clear about which sense is intended.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The various ways to apply prefixes and suffixes can also create ambiguity ("unlockable" can mean "capable of being opened" or "impossible to lock").
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Semantic ambiguity occurs when a word, phrase, or sentence has more than one possible interpretation.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] 2. an action the woman performed (verb phrase with *duck* as a verb and *her* as the object of *saw*).
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] "We saw her duck" contains syntactic ambiguity in addition to semantic ambiguity.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Syntactic ambiguity arises when a sentence can have different meanings because of the structure of the sentence, or syntax.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] This is often due to a modifying expression, such as a prepositional phrase, the application of which is unclear.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] For example, the sentence "He ate the cookies on the couch" could mean that he ate the cookies that were on the couch (as opposed to those that were on the table), or it could mean that he was sitting on the couch when he ate the cookies.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Only rewriting the sentence or placing appropriate punctuation can resolve a syntactic ambiguity.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] For syntactic ambiguity in formal languages (such as computer programming languages), see ambiguous grammar.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Conversely, a sentence like "He ate the cookies on the couch" is also semantically ambiguous.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Rarely, but occasionally, the different parsings of a syntactically ambiguous phrase result in the same meaning.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Spoken language can contain many more types of ambiguities that are called phonological ambiguities, where there is more than one way to compose a set of sounds into words, such as "ice cream" and "I scream".
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Such ambiguity is generally resolved according to the context.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] A mishearing of such, based on incorrectly resolved ambiguity, is called a mondegreen.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Philosophers (and other users of logic) spend a lot of time and effort searching for and removing (or intentionally adding) ambiguity in arguments because it can lead to incorrect conclusions and can be used to deliberately conceal bad arguments.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] For example, a politician might say, "I oppose taxes which hinder economic growth", an example of a glittering generality.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Some will think they oppose taxes in general because they hinder economic growth.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Others may think they oppose only those taxes that they believe will hinder economic growth.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In writing, the sentence can be rewritten to reduce possible misinterpretation, either by adding a comma after "taxes" (to convey the first sense), or by changing "which" to "that" (to convey the second sense), or by rewriting it in other ways.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The devious politician hopes that each constituent will interpret the statement in the most desirable way, and think the politician supports everyone's opinion.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] However, the opposite can also be true—an opponent can turn a positive statement into a bad one if the speaker uses ambiguity (intentionally or not).
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The logical fallacies of amphiboly and equivocation rely heavily on the use of ambiguous words and phrases.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In continental philosophy (particularly phenomenology and existentialism), there is much greater tolerance of ambiguity, as it is generally seen as an integral part of the human condition.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Martin Heidegger argued that the relation between the subject and object is ambiguous, as is the relation of mind and body and part and whole.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In Heidegger's phenomenology, Dasein is always in a meaningful world, but there is always an underlying background for every instance of signification.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Thus, although some things may be certain, they have little to do with Dasein's sense of care and existential anxiety, e.g., in the face of death.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In calling his work Being and Nothingness an "essay in phenomenological ontology" Jean-Paul Sartre follows Heidegger in defining the human essence as ambiguous, or relating fundamentally to such ambiguity.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Ethics cannot be based on the authoritative certainty given by mathematics and logic, or prescribed directly from the empirical findings of science.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] She states: "Since we do not succeed in fleeing it, let us, therefore, try to look the truth in the face.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Let us try to assume our fundamental ambiguity.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] It is in the knowledge of the genuine conditions of our life that we must draw our strength to live and our reason for acting".
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In literature and rhetoric, ambiguity can be a useful tool.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Groucho Marx's classic joke depends on a grammatical ambiguity for its humor, for example: "Last night I shot an elephant in my pajamas.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] How he got in my pajamas, I'll never know".
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Songs and poetry often rely on ambiguous words for artistic effect, as in the song title "Don't It Make My Brown Eyes Blue" (where "blue" can refer to the color or to sadness).
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In the narrative, ambiguity can be introduced in several ways: motive, plot, and character.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Scott Fitzgerald uses the latter type of ambiguity with notable effect in his novel *The Great Gatsby*.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Mathematical notation is a helpful tool that eliminates a lot of misunderstandings associated with natural language in physics and other sciences.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Nonetheless, there are still some inherent ambiguities due to lexical, syntactic, and semantic reasons that persist in mathematical notation.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The ambiguity in the style of writing a function should not be confused with a multivalued function, which can (and should) be defined in a deterministic and unambiguous way.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Several special functions still do not have established notations.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Usually, the conversion to another notation requires scaling the argument or the resulting value; sometimes, the same name of the function is used, causing confusion.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Ambiguous expressions often appear in physical and mathematical texts.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] It is common practice to omit multiplication signs in mathematical expressions.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Also, it is common to give the same name to a variable and a function, for example, $f=f(x)$ .
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Then, if one sees $f=f(y+1)$ , there is no way to distinguish whether it means $f=f(x)$ **multiplied** by $(y+1)$ , or function f **evaluated** at argument equal to $(y+1)$ .
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In each case of use of such notations, the reader is supposed to be able to perform the deduction and reveal the true meaning.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Creators of algorithmic languages try to avoid ambiguities.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Many algorithmic languages (C++ and Fortran) require the character * as a symbol of multiplication.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The Wolfram Language used in Mathematica allows the user to omit the multiplication symbol but requires square brackets to indicate the argument of a function; square brackets are not allowed for grouping of expressions.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Fortran, in addition, does not allow the use of the same name (identifier) for different objects, for example, a function and a variable; in particular, the expression $f=f(x)$ is qualified as an error.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The order of operations may depend on the context.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In most programming languages, the operations of division and multiplication have equal priority and are executed from left to right.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Until the last century, many editorials assumed that multiplication is performed first, for example, $a/bc$ is interpreted as $a/(bc)$ ; in this case, the insertion of parentheses is required when translating the formulas to an algorithmic language.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In addition, it is common to write an argument of a function without parentheses, which also may lead to ambiguity.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In the scientific journal style, one uses Roman letters to denote elementary functions, whereas variables are written using italics.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] For example, in mathematical journals the expression $sin$ does not denote the sine function but the product of the three variables s , i , n , although in the informal notation of a slide presentation it may stand for $\sin$ .
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Commas in multi-component subscripts and superscripts are sometimes omitted; this is also potentially ambiguous notation.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] For example, in the notation $T_{mnk}$ , the reader can only infer from the context whether it means a single-index object, taken with the subscript equal to the product of variables m , n and k , or it is an indication of a trivalent tensor.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Often the author's intention can be understood from the context, in cases where only one of the two makes sense, but an ambiguity like this should be avoided, for example by writing $\sin ^{2}(\alpha /2)$ or ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\sin ^{2}\alpha }$ .
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The expression $\sin ^{-1}\alpha$ means $\arcsin(\alpha )$ in several texts, though it might be thought to mean $(\sin \alpha )^{-1}$ , since $\sin ^{n}\alpha$ commonly means $(\sin \alpha )^{n}$ .
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Conversely, $\sin ^{2}\alpha$ might seem to mean $\sin(\sin \alpha )$ , as this exponentiation notation usually denotes function iteration: in general, $f^{2}(x)$ means $f(f(x))$ .
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] However, for trigonometric and hyperbolic functions, this notation conventionally means exponentiation of the result of function application.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The expression $a/2b$ can be interpreted as meaning $(a/2)b$ ; however, it is more commonly understood to mean $a/(2b)$ .
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] It is common to define the coherent states in quantum optics with $~|\alpha \rangle ~$ and states with a fixed number of photons with $~|n\rangle ~$ .
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Then, there is an "unwritten rule": the state is coherent if there are more Greek characters than Latin characters in the argument and n -photon state if the Latin characters dominate.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The ambiguity becomes even worse, if $~|x\rangle ~$ is used for the states with a certain value of the coordinate and $~|p\rangle ~$ means the state with a certain value of the momentum, which may be used in books on quantum mechanics.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Such ambiguities easily lead to confusions, especially if some normalized adimensional, dimensionless variables are used.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Expression $|1\rangle$ may mean a state with a single photon, or the coherent state with mean amplitude equal to 1, or state with momentum equal to unity, and so on.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The reader is supposed to guess from the context.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Some physical quantities do not yet have established notations; their value (and sometimes even dimension, as in the case of the Einstein coefficients) depends on the system of notations.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Each use of an ambiguous term should be preceded by the definition suitable for a specific case.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Just like Ludwig Wittgenstein states in Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus: "...
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] For example, the sentence "the gain of a system should be doubled", without context, means close to nothing.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The term *intensity* is ambiguous when applied to light.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The term can refer to any of irradiance, luminous intensity, radiant intensity, or radiance, depending on the background of the person using the term.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Also, confusions may be related to the use of atomic percent as a measure of concentration of a dopant or resolution of an imaging system as a measure of the size of the smallest detail that can be resolved at the background of statistical noise.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The Berry paradox arises as a result of systematic ambiguity in the meaning of terms such as "definable" or "nameable".
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Terms of this kind give rise to vicious circle fallacies.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Other terms with this type of ambiguity are: satisfiable, true, false, function, property, class, relation, cardinal, and ordinal.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Logical ambiguity and self-contradiction are analogous to visual ambiguity and impossible objects, such as the Necker cube and impossible cube, or many of the drawings of M.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Ambiguity in the social sciences refers to situations, meanings, identities, or social arrangements that resist clear classification or stable interpretation.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Rather than viewing ambiguity as a problem to be resolved, scholars examine how uncertainty, indeterminacy, and multiplicity are actively lived, negotiated, and sometimes strategically maintained in social life.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Across anthropology, sociology, and political theory, ambiguity has been used to analyse crisis, governance, moral reasoning, and social change, highlighting how people navigate competing norms, values, and futures.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Attention to ambiguity foregrounds lived experience, affect, and power, showing how social actors make sense of complex worlds where outcomes, roles, and meanings remain unsettled.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Social scientists note that ambiguity has been examined or investigated across many disciplines concerned with knowledge and knowledge production, including mathematics, philosophy, logic, and the natural, behavioural, and social sciences.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] They show that these fields have variously treated ambiguity as something to control, resolve, or strategically use.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In anthropology, early efforts to define and classify social and cultural life were similarly shaped by ambiguity, as categories were often marked by exceptions, contradictions, and overlap.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Foundational studies of boundaries—such as those between the sacred and profane, purity and pollution, and myth and meaning—demonstrated how social order operates despite continual flux and indeterminacy.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Some languages have been created with the intention of avoiding ambiguity, especially lexical ambiguity.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Lojban and Loglan are two related languages that have been created for this, focusing chiefly on syntactic ambiguity.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The languages can be both spoken and written.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] These languages are intended to provide greater technical precision over natural languages, although historically, such attempts at language improvement have been criticized.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Languages composed from many diverse sources contain much ambiguity and inconsistency.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The many exceptions to syntax and semantic rules are time-consuming and difficult to learn.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In structural biology, ambiguity has been recognized as a problem for studying protein conformations.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The analysis of a protein's three-dimensional structure consists in dividing the macromolecule into subunits called domains.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The difficulty of this task arises from the fact that different definitions of what a domain is can be used (e.g., folding autonomy, function, thermodynamic stability, or domain motions), which sometimes results in a single protein having different—yet equally valid—domain assignments.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Christianity and Judaism employ the concept of paradox synonymously with "ambiguity".
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Many Christians and Jews endorse Rudolf Otto's description of the sacred as 'mysterium tremendum et fascinans,' the awe-inspiring mystery that fascinates humans.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Chesterton regularly employed paradox to tease out the meanings in common concepts that he found ambiguous or to reveal meaning often overlooked or forgotten in common phrases: the title of one of his most famous books, *Orthodoxy* (1908), itself employed such a paradox.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In music, pieces or sections that confound expectations and may be, or are, interpreted simultaneously in different ways are ambiguous.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Examples being some polytonality, polymeter, other ambiguous meters or rhythms, and ambiguous phrasing, or (Stein 2005, p.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The music of Africa is often purposely ambiguous .
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] To quote Sir Donald Francis Tovey (1935, p.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In visual art, certain images are visually ambiguous, such as the Necker cube, which can be interpreted in two ways.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Perceptions of such objects remain stable for a time, then may flip, a phenomenon called multistable perception.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] The opposite of such ambiguous images are impossible objects.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In social psychology, ambiguity is a factor used in determining people's responses to various situations.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] High levels of ambiguity in an emergency (e.g., an unconscious man lying on a park bench) make witnesses less likely to offer any sort of assistance, due to the fear that they may have misinterpreted the situation and acted unnecessarily.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] Alternately, non-ambiguous emergencies (e.g., an injured person verbally asking for help) elicit more consistent intervention and assistance.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] With regard to the bystander effect, studies have shown that emergencies deemed ambiguous trigger the appearance of the classic bystander effect (wherein more witnesses decrease the likelihood of them helping) far more than non-ambiguous emergencies.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] In computer science, the SI prefixes *kilo-*, *mega-*, and *giga-* were historically used in certain contexts to mean either the first three powers of 1024 (1024, 10242, and 10243), contrary to the metric system, in which these units unambiguously mean one thousand, one million, and one billion.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] This usage is particularly prevalent with electronic memory devices (e.g., DRAM) addressed directly by a binary machine register where a decimal interpretation makes no practical sense.
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] 1 M (where M is ambiguously 1000000 or 1048576) is *less* uncertain than the engineering value 1.0×106 (defined to designate the interval 950000 to 1050000).
[src:ambiguity/ambiguity] As non-volatile storage devices begin to exceed 1 GB in capacity (where the ambiguity begins to routinely impact the second significant digit), GB and TB almost always mean 109 and 1012 bytes.
